<font color="#FF0000">I REMEMBER VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 12  0:46:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The thing I remember most about VN was the news. I remember watching the every news every night so I could maybe determine how much danger my husband had been in that day (he was a B-52 pilot that flew over NVN). I remember waiting for the mailman to come, because he wrote everyday. I remember the women of the other pilots in the crew doing similar things. I remember talking to some of them ALOT. What I remember most was the knock on the door and three strangers standing there telling me my husband had been killed. An I remember thinking how am I going to survive with two small children. I wasn't prepared for this - yes, I knew it could happen - but I wasn't prepared. It was terrible and lonely and scary and I didn't think I could raise two children alone. And my friends who were wives of the crew weren't my friends anymore because they still had their husbands, but I didn't have mine. And I remember a neighbor saying &quot;life goes on&quot;. Well, it didn't for me. That life was over and I didn't know what the new one would be. And no one was there only me. I'm a psychologist now and I work with kids that have experienced trauma. I think I became a psychologist just so I could understand what happened to me. I'm glad this is here. Because no one else would understand.
<p><code>-- FryknFrack@aol.com  (Merikay) </code><p>


